Author

Xiaojing Ni

Stream flow

Detect the trend

Code 
trend_discharge = ma(discharge_ts, order = 365, centre = T)
plot(discharge_ts, main="Stream flow discharge at Waterville, OH station",ylab=expression(paste("Discharge, ",ft^3,"/s",sep="")))
lines(trend_discharge, col = 2, lwd = 4)
legend(14000, 115000, legend=c("Observation", "Trend"),
       col=c("black", "red"), pch = c(1, NA),lty=1)

Figure 1 shows the daily stream flow trend obtained by moving average method with order of 365 (annual). There is no clear trend based on this figure.

Code 
## detrend
x = seq(0,20000,20000/5)
y = seq(1970,2020,10)
detrend_discharge = discharge_ts/trend_discharge
plot(as.ts(detrend_discharge),xaxt='n',main="Detrend Discharge",ylab=expression(paste("Discharge, ",ft^3,"/s",sep="")))
axis(side = 1, at = x, labels = y)

Seasonality

Code 
## Average the Seasonality
m_discharge = t(matrix(data = detrend_discharge, nrow = 365))

seasonal_discharge = colMeans(m_discharge, na.rm = T)
plot(as.ts(rep(seasonal_discharge,50)),main="Stream Flow Discharge Average Seasonality",ylab=expression(paste("Discharge, ",ft^3,"/s",sep="")),xaxt='n')
axis(side = 1, at = x,labels = y)

Figure 2 shows the detrened series. There is clear seasonality left in the series. Both multiplicative and additive have non-stationary residuals. Thus, more analysis need to be done other then detrending.

Lags

Figure 4 shows the lag plot for daily and monthly stream flow discharge. For daily stream flow discharge (Figure 4 (a)), it shows the most related time is lag1, which makes sense that the next day stream flow discharge highly depends on the previous day. For monthly stream flow discharge (Figure 4 (b)), it seems there is no clear pattern.

Code 
discharge_month2022 <- window(discharge_month,start=1980,end=2022)
decompose_discharge <- decompose(as.ts(discharge_month2022), "additive")
plot(decompose_discharge)

Figure 5 is the decomposition for monthly stream flow discharge. we can see the residual is more stationary compared to detrended daily stream flow discharge in Figure 2. Next, we will use ACF and PACF plot to see if the residual is stationary.

ACF and PACF

Code 
## ACF

ggAcf(discharge_month,400)
ggPacf(discharge_month,400)
Code 
################ ADF Test #############
tseries::adf.test(discharge_month2022)

    Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test

data:  discharge_month2022
Dickey-Fuller = -10.302, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
alternative hypothesis: stationary

Figure 6 shows that the monthly stream flow discharge is not stationary. Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test confirms this. Next, we will use detrened series to see if the residual is stationary. Figure 7 shows the detrended series still have unsolved pattern left. Other analysis need to be done further.

Code 
## ACF
detrend <- discharge_month2022/decompose_discharge$trend
ggAcf(detrend,400)
ggPacf(detrend,400)

################ ADF Test #############
tseries::adf.test(window(detrend, 1981,2020))

Moving average smoothing

Code 
## daily plot
discharge_daily <- ts(discharge$discharge,star=decimal_date(as.Date("1970-01-01",format = "%Y-%m-%d")),frequency = 365.25)

p <- autoplot(discharge_daily, series="Observation") +
  autolayer(ma(discharge_daily, 30), series="30-MA (Monthly)") + 
  autolayer(ma(discharge_daily, 365), series="365-MA (Annual)") + 
  autolayer(ma(discharge_daily, 1460), series="1460-MA (Four-year)") +
  xlab("Year") + ylab(expression(paste("Discharge, ",ft^3,"/s",sep=""))) +
  ggtitle("daily stream flow") +
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("Observation"="grey","1460-MA (Four-year)"="green","365-MA (Annual)"="red", "30-MA (Monthly)"="blue"),
                      breaks=c("Observation","1460-MA (Four-year)","365-MA (Annual)", "30-MA (Monthly)"))
p
Code 
### can get monthly data
# Get mean value for each month
mean_data <- discharge %>% 
  mutate(month = month(date), year = year(date)) %>% 
  group_by(year, month) %>% 
  summarize(mean_value = mean(as.numeric(as.vector(discharge)),na.rm = TRUE))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
Code 
discharge_monthly<-ts(mean_data$mean_value,star=decimal_date(as.Date("1970-01-01",format = "%Y-%m-%d")),frequency = 12)

p <- autoplot(discharge_monthly, series="Observation") +
  autolayer(ma(discharge_monthly, 12), series="12-MA (Annual)") + 
  autolayer(ma(discharge_monthly, 48), series="48-MA (Four-year)") +
  xlab("Year") + ylab(expression(paste("Discharge, ",ft^3,"/s",sep=""))) +
  ggtitle("daily stream flow") +
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("Observation"="grey","48-MA (Four-year)"="green","12-MA (Annual)"="red"),
                      breaks=c("Observation","48-MA (Four-year)","12-MA (Annual)"))
p

The annual moving average shows periodicity. Thus, a larger window, four-year window, is used to explore the pattern of the streamflow. we can see the four-year moving average is more stationary compared to others.
